If Walleye and Sauger catch continue to be low, at the very least, the second survey would add to the sample to better reflect Walleye and Sauger length frequency, age and growth, and add power to the total mortality estimates.

Data collected from an ongoing acoustic telemetry project may help gill netting efforts. Twenty Walleyes were implanted with acoustic transmitters in 2015, of which 10 had temperature and depth sensors. One transmitter was recovered on shore in 2017 and was not implanted in a new fish. The 19 remaining transmitters at large were all expected to cease transmissions on 10/30/18. This data could provide key insights to Walleye locations and depths throughout the year. However, early telemetry analysis shows a 26-36% reduction of Walleyes at large per year. This could be due to mortality or fish residing in areas out of range of the passive acoustic receivers. Detailed analysis may inform future sampling to increase catch and efficiency.

Although overall net catches were down, many species sampled in the nets were within their historical ranges since standard netting practices were adopted in 1992. Of the 522 total fish sampled, 282 (54%) were considered to be game species. The five most abundant game fish species sampled by number were yellow perch, white bass, bluegill, black crappie, and channel catfish. Nongame species sampled were comprised mostly of the sucker family (62.9%), most of which were redhorse species. Two species, silver redhorse and freshwater drum, were responsible for 62% of the nongame species sampled and 28.5% of all species sampled.
Walleye sampled ranged in size from 9.84 to 27.56-in long. Based on back calculated length-at-age, the average walleye reaches the minimum harvestable size of 15-in by age 3, which generally agrees with past data. The largest walleye was aged using otoliths and was aged as 15-years-old. Sauger gill net catch per lift was 1.13, the lowest in recent sampling history. Lengths ranged from 8.58 to 18.35-in long. The oldest and largest sauger was aged as 5-years-old using otoliths.
Only 13 smallmouth bass were sampled in the nets. The 0.75 smallmouth bass per gill net lift was the highest value since standardized netting began in 1992. However, electrofishing is the preferred method for assessing smallmouth bass populations. The largest smallmouth bass sampled was 14.25-in long and weighed 1.36 lbs. Based on the limited smallmouth bass data collected, legal harvestable size (14-inches) is not attained until after the fish reaches 4 years of age. This generally agrees with past data.
White bass gill net catch per lift was 2.75 and within the recent historical range. Lengths ranged from 7.09 to 15.83-in and the largest white bass weighed 1.85 lbs. The oldest white bass, as determined by otoliths, were 6-years-old. Mean length-at-capture was 12-in for 2-year-old fish. White bass likely reach harvestable size, generally nine inches, before they reach their second winter.
Channel catfish number per gill net set was 1.75, the lowest it has been since the standard survey methods were adopted in 1992. The highest number of channel catfish per gill net lift occurred in 1997 when it was 4.19. A slow steady decline in catch per lift has been observed since then in 2002 and 2006. Channel catfish length-at-age is highly variable and was no different in this survey. Lengths overlapped considerably for channel catfish aged as 6-8 years old and those lengths ranged from 16.55 to 21.16-in long. The 16-year-old channel catfish was only 21.47-in long. The largest channel catfish sampled (26.69-in) was 9-years-old. Additionally, four flathead catfish were sampled and the largest was 23.07-in long and weighed 4.73 lbs. Spines were removed from all four flathead catfish and ages determined to be 5, 6, 8, and 9 years old.
Forty bluegill were sampled, all in trap nets, which resulted in 1.74 bluegill per trap net lift. This is within the range of recent surveys. The largest bluegill sampled was 7.83-in long and weighed 0.38 lb. Eighteen (45%) of the bluegill sampled were at least seven inches long. Back-calculated mean length-at-age was comparable to recent surveys, if not a little faster after age 2. A quality and fast growing 2006 year class greatly influenced these numbers.
Forty-four yellow perch were sampled in gill nets (2.75/lift) and was the highest perch catch rate of recent fishery surveys in Lake St. Croix. Most (86.3%) of the yellow perch sampled were below the minimum generally accepted angler harvest size of eight inches. The largest yellow perch sampled was 11.26-in long, weighed 0.66 lb, and was caught in a trap net.
Small numbers of both black crappie and white crappie were sampled in this survey. Thirty total black crappie were sampled, 25 from trap nets. Six white crappie were collected, all from gill nets. This low catch of crappie is not unexpected as it is comparable to recent historical data. The largest crappie sampled was a black crappie and was 9.84-in long, and three black crappie sampled weighed a half pound or more.
Low numbers of northern pike and lake sturgeon were also sampled and the catch rates were comparable to recent surveys. Although muskellunge are stocked in both the St. Croix River and Lake St. Croix, none were sampled.

Our goal in the 2014 survey was to determine if increased gill net effort would catch more Walleye and Sauger for a more detailed analysis of their respective populations and to determine if better locations could be selected for new standard sites to increase sampling efficiency of these popular sport fish. An experimental survey design was developed to target Walleye and Sauger to learn more about their respective populations in Lake St. Croix. The Lake was divided into four segments with increased gill net sets in each segment. The segments were defined as follows: Segment 1, the Stillwater Lift Bridge to the Railroad Bridge near Hudson, WI; Segment 2, the Hudson Railroad Bridge to Catfish Bar; Segment 3, Catfish Bar to the Kinnickinnic River Narrows; Segment 4, the Kinnickinnic River Narrows to the mouth of the St. Croix River near Prescott, WI. Twenty gill nets were to be set in each segment, and two segments were to be netted in September each year, with all four segments being completed in two years. At the end of the two year sampling period, net catches were to be evaluated to determine if certain locations could yield a higher catch of Walleye and Sauger to develop new standard nets sites with higher catch rates of targeted species that would require less effort to duplicate in future sampling years. Another experiment was conducted by suspending a small number of gill nets to determine if Walleye and Sauger may be sampled higher in the water column, presumably while chasing bait fish such as Gizzard Shad.

Segment 2 and Segment 4 were chosen for the first year of sampling, which began on September 22, 2014. Prior to setting nets, temperature and dissolved oxygen profiles were taken for each segment to ensure that nets were not set in areas of low dissolved oxygen, which would reduce the catch of Walleye and Sauger. Fall turnover had already occurred as dissolved oxygen was above 6 parts per million as deep as 50-feet and the temperature difference between the surface and 50-feet was less than two degrees Fahrenheit for both segments.

Twenty gill nets were set in Segment 2 and 15 were set in Segment 4. Five fewer nets were set in Segment 4 as a large number of fish were being sampled and the remaining locations to set nets were high traffic boat areas. It was determined the 15 nets set in Segment 4 were sufficient. A total of 793 fish were sampled represented by 23 different species and one hybrid (Sauger/Walleye hybrid). Over 54% of the fish sampled were considered game fish species. The top five game fish species sampled were Sauger (155), Walleye (64), Channel Catfish (64), Yellow Perch (59), and White Bass (24). Of the 362 non-game fish species sampled, over 56% were Freshwater Drum. Although Freshwater Drum are considered a non-game species, they are frequently harvested from the St. Croix River and are commonly the most harvested non-game fish. In fact, the most recent creel survey conducted on Lake St. Croix in 2013 estimated Freshwater Drum harvest almost tripled the Channel Catfish harvest during the open water season. Freshwater Drum were also the most caught and released fish in the 2013 open water creel survey. Much of the remaining non-game fish sampled in this survey were Gizzard Shad, Mooneye, Gar species, and Redhorse species.

Catch rates for Walleye and Sauger were above the average from the previous five surveys. Walleye catch/gill net lift (1.83) was the highest observed since 1973 and Sauger was within the range of historical surveys (4.43/lift). The mean number of Walleye sampled/lift in the five previous surveys was 1.04. The mean number of Sauger sampled/lift in the five previous surveys was 3.23. The number/lift for both species was within the range of past surveys, but the increased number of Walleye and Sauger collected was much higher than past surveys because of the increased number of nets. A total of 64 Walleye and 155 Sauger were sampled. However, the number of fish/lift could be misleading because of the poor suspended gill net catch. Seven gill nets were set suspended 10-15-feet from the water's surface to see if Walleye and Sauger catch increased while chasing bait fish. Only three Walleye and four Sauger were sampled in suspended gill nets. Omitting the suspended nets, the Walleye and Sauger/gill net lift increased to 2.18 and 5.39, respectively.

Mean weight for Walleye sampled was 1.15-pounds and was below the unweighted mean weight from the five previous surveys (1.27-pounds), but within the range from those surveys. Just over 39% of the Walleye sampled were 15-in or larger, and just over 6% were 20-in or larger. The largest Walleye sampled was 26.85-in long and weighed 7.61-lbs. Sauger mean weight (0.72) was slightly above the unweighted mean of the five previous surveys (0.66-lbs) and also within the range of those surveys. Over 74% of the Sauger sampled were 12-in or larger, and just over 19% were 15-in or larger. The largest Sauger sampled was 20.28-in long and weighed 2.19-lbs.

All 64 Walleye were aged using otoliths. Ages ranged from 0 (young-of-the-year) to 10-years-old. On average, Walleye reach the 15-in minimum length limit for harvest at 3-years-old. Some 2-year-old individuals reach the 15-in minimum length limit in the fall. The largest Walleye sampled (26.9-in) was aged as 9-years-old. The oldest walleye sampled (10-years-old) was only 23.3-in long. Over 84% of the Walleye sampled were 3-years-old or younger.

Three of the 155 Sauger sampled were unable to be aged accurately. Ages for the 152 Sauger ranged from 1 to 6-years-old with 2 and 3-year-olds being the most common age classes sampled (65 2-years-old, 41 3-years-old). Mean length-at-age-2 was 12.3-in, which is generally considered the minimum harvestable size desired by anglers. Three Sauger were aged at 6-years-old and their lengths ranged from 15.2 to 20.3-in.

Black Crappie catch/lift was 0.66. The mean catch/lift for the last five surveys since 1992 is 0.86. Twenty of the 23 Black Crappie sampled had otoliths removed for aging. Ages 1 through 6 were represented in this survey and 60% of those aged were 4-years-old. Mean length-at-age-2 was 9.9-in and the largest Black Crappie sampled (12.4-in) was aged as 5-years-old. The oldest Black Crappie was 6-years-old and measured 11.9-in. There was little difference in mean length-at-age for ages 2 through 4 (2-years-old, 9.9-in; 3-years-old, 10.3-in; 4-years-old, 10.6-in).

The Yellow Perch population appeared to be expanding when the catch/lift increased from 1.44/lift in 2006 to 2.75/lift in 2009. This survey captured 59 Yellow Perch resulting in 1.69/lift. This is slightly above the mean catch/lift from 1992-2009. After reviewing older survey data, prior to the new gill netting standard set forth in 1992, the Yellow Perch population appears to be stable. The highest Yellow Perch catch/lift was 3.56 and occurred in 1988. Fifty-three out of the 59 Yellow Perch sampled were aged using otoliths. Ages ranged from 1 to 5-years-old. The oldest Yellow Perch sampled (5-years-old) was 10.1-in long. There was little difference in mean length-at-age for ages 2 through 4 (2-years-old, 8.2-in; 3-years-old, 8.2-in; 4-years-old, 8.5-in).

This survey had the lowest White Bass catch of any survey conducted since 1967. Only 24 White Bass were sampled in this survey (0.69/lift). The mean catch/lift since 1992 is 3.03. It is not known if the later survey date is responsible for such a low White Bass catch rate. All 24 White Bass were aged using otoliths and represented all ages from 1 through 9, except age 7. The oldest and largest White Bass (16-in) was 9-years-old. White Bass reach the generally accepted 9-in minimum harvestable length by age-1. Mean length-at-age for age-1 White Bass was 9.6-in and ranged from 8.6 to 10.9-in.

Sixty-four Channel Catfish were sampled resulting in 1.83/lift. This catch rate is below the mean from the last five surveys since 1992 (3.30/lift), but is within the range expected, especially when compared to historical data back to 1967. Spines were not obtained from Channel Catfish for aging. However, eight of the 64 Channel Catfish sampled were tagged with Carlin Disc Dangler tags as a continuation of a catfish tagging project that started in 2009. The mean length of tagged Channel Catfish was 19.5-in with a minimum length of 14.6-in and maximum length of 31.3-in.

Three Lake Sturgeon were sampled in this survey and ranged in length from 23.4 to 25.9-inches long. All three were tagged with Carlin Disc Dangler tags and Passive Integrated Transponder (PIT) tags as a continuation of a Lake Sturgeon tagging project initiated in 2003.

This gill netting evaluation is to continue with Segments 1 and 3 scheduled to be sampled in September, 2015. After the last two Segments are completed, data will be re-evaluated to determine future sampling methods and survey frequency. It is recommended to discontinue the suspended gill net sets as overall fish catch was low and very few Walleye and Sauger were sampled in those nets. Aging common game fish using otoliths will continue as that is the best methodology available to obtain accurate fish ages.

Two gill net surveys were conducted on Lake St. Croix in 2022. The standard survey schedule in mid-September was followed with a second survey utilizing the same net locations the last week of October. These two surveys combined sampled 984 fish represented by 27 different species. Over 64% of the fish sampled were considered game fish species (those species which have defined creel limits). The top five game fish species sampled were White Bass (218), Yellow Perch (113), Walleye (89), Channel Catfish (88), and Smallmouth Bass (50). Of the 350 non-game fish sampled, 22.3% were Shorthead Redhorse, 18.3% were Gizzard Shad, 16.3% were Silver Redhorse, and Freshwater Drum were 15.7%.

The 2022 Walleye catch rate of 3.71/lift was down 1% from the 2021 survey but was still above the 2016-2021 average in the new net locations and was the third highest catch/lift in the last 30 years. Sauger catch rates have been highly variable the last 30 years but were relatively stable from 2016-2020 with an average catch rate of 3.36/lift. The 2021 Sauger catch of 4.25/lift was well above the average from the 2016-2020 surveys utilizing the new net locations but the 2022 catch of 2.04 Saugers/lift was well below the 2016-2021 average of 3.53/lift, down 52% from 2021.

Average length for all measured Walleyes was 15.45 inches, slightly below the 2016-2021 average of 15.58 inches. Over 47% of Walleyes sampled were over 15 inches and almost 17% exceeded 18 inches, both down from the 2021 survey. The largest Walleye sampled in 2022 was 24.92 inches and 5.51 pounds. Average weight (0.91 pounds) for Saugers was almost identical to the average (0.90 pounds) from the 2016-2021 surveys. Average length for all Saugers sampled was 13.86 inches, slightly below the average of 14.03 from 2016-2021. Almost 76% of the Saugers sampled were 12 inches or larger, and almost 27% were 15 inches or larger, both decreases from 2021. The largest Sauger sampled was 20.43 inches and 3.09 pounds and was the longest sampled in over 30 years.

Only four Black Crappies were sampled in 2022, of which three were collected in the October survey. Only one White Crappie was sampled in 2022 and was 10.12 inches long. Gill netting is not a good indicator of the crappie population present in the St. Croix River. The importance of crappie to the winter fishery on Lake St. Croix may warrant further sampling, such as spring trap netting, to evaluate a population of such importance to the winter creel.

The Yellow Perch population appears to be improving to a point where it can be a more important component to the sport fishery. 2022 had the second highest catch rate (4.71/lift) of Yellow Perch since fall gill netting began in 2014. The catch/lift decreased slightly (12%) from the September 2022 survey to the October 2022 survey. In 2021, 72.4% of the Yellow Perch sampled were less than 8 inches with an average length of 7.27 inches and the largest individual was 11.26 inches. In 2022, 56.7% of the Yellow Perch were less than 8 inches, the average length increased to 7.88 inches and the largest individual sampled was again 11.26 inches.

The 2022 White Bass catch (9.08/lift) was the highest catch observed for the second year in a row since 1992 and almost triple the average catch rate from 1992-2021. The catch/lift decreased 57% from the September 2022 survey to the October 2022 survey. Strong year classes in 2015, 2017, 2020, and 2021 have been represented well in each successive survey. White Bass fishing should continue to be good the next few years as the strong year classes progress to larger sizes and is well documented in the last several surveys. Over 73% of the White Bass measured were 12 inches or larger. The largest White Bass sampled in 2022 was a 17.72 inch, 10-year-old male, and weighed 2.65 pounds. Interestingly, that White Bass was immature, which is odd considering that over 50% of males sampled since 2014 mature at age-1 and all older males have been mature.

In 2022, the Channel Catfish catch (3.67/lift) was the highest observed since 1997 and the highest observed in the new fall gill net locations. The catch has been trending up since 2015 following a steady decline from 1992-2015. Catch/lift increased slightly (15%) from the September 2022 survey to the October 2022 survey. Almost 55% of the Channel Catfish sampled in this survey were at least 16 inches long. The two largest Channel Catfish sampled in this survey were 27.2 inches and 9.92 pounds, the other 27.44 inches and 8.71 pounds.

Only one Lake Sturgeon was sampled in this survey (0.04/lift). Another Lake Sturgeon escaped the gill net as it was being retrieved. At least one Lake Sturgeon has been sampled in every gill net survey since 1973.

Smallmouth Bass are typically caught in such few numbers in Lake St. Croix gill net surveys that they rarely deserve mention. However, the 2021 and 2022 surveys had the highest catch rate observed since standardized surveys began in 1992. While 2.08 Smallmouth Bass/lift is still a low number, the average catch/lift (1.11) from the fall surveys from 2014-2022 is more than double the average catch/lift (0.41) in summer surveys from 1992-2009. Catch rates appear to increase later in the fall as the catch increased 113% from the September 2021 survey to the November 2021 survey and experienced a similar increase of 133% from the September 2022 survey to the October 2022 survey. Thirty-four percent of the Smallmouth Bass sampled exceeded 14 inches with the largest being 20.08 inches and 4.89 pounds which is the largest since 1997.

While the surveys from 2016-2018 with revised net locations and reduced effort were disappointing, the large 2018 Walleye year class made 2020 the best gill net survey ever observed for Walleye in Lake St. Croix, 2021 survey was the second best, and 2022 the third best. A fall survey in late October/early November appears to be a suitable replacement for the September survey. In November 2021, catch of non-target species declined 25%, while Sauger catch increased 62% and Walleye increased 50% when compared to the September 2021 survey. Unfortunately, secondary target species like Channel Catfish and White Bass decreased 26% and 59% respectively. In October 2022, catch of non-target species declined 35%, while Sauger catch increased 106% and Walleye increased 87% when compared to the September 2022 survey. Unfortunately, secondary target species like White Bass decreased 57% but the Channel Catfish catch increased 15% in 2022. Other game species that appear to have altered catch rates between the fall surveys are Yellow Perch, which declines later in the fall, and Smallmouth Bass, which increases later in the fall.

It is recommended to continue the annual gill net assessment in Lake St. Croix with the current number of net sets (12) and net locations but change to a late October/early November survey schedule. Decreased by-catch and increased catch rates of primary target species would greatly increase efficiency. September can now be used to explore developing a standardized assessment for Lake Sturgeon as well as targeted sampling to increase the number of tagged Lake Sturgeon.

The overall fishing forecast looks promising for the next few years depending on the species. The strong 2018 Walleye year-class does not appear to have persisted as the number of 4-year-old Walleyes sampled was relatively low, which is typical on Lake St. Croix. Most Walleyes over the 15-inch minimum length limit that will be available to angler harvest will be from the 2019 and 2020 year-classes with the occasional older, larger fish. Sauger numbers are not as strong as Walleye and have been relatively low since 2015. Most of the Saugers sampled were from the 2020 year-class and will provide some harvest opportunities. White Bass fishing could be the best it has been in decades. The fast-growing 2021 and 2022 White Bass year-classes should provide good numbers of harvestable White Bass and the strong 2015, 2017, and 2020 year-classes could produce numerous high-quality fish over 14 inches and even over 16 inches. Channel Catfish numbers and size continues to improve and should provide a worthwhile target for anglers. The Yellow Perch population may have finally grown to a point where it may provide some increased harvest opportunities. It will be interesting to monitor the Yellow Perch over the next few years to see if the fish continue to grow to larger sizes, potentially contributing more to the recreational fishery. The 2022 survey, like the 2021 survey, was the best sample ever for Smallmouth Bass. A decent Smallmouth Bass fishery exists in Lake St. Croix, although the gill net surveys rarely reflect that.
